    Obscure error: Expected a value of type 'List[int]' for argument 'sizes' but instead found type 'immutable_list'#122129
    Copy link

    Description

    ezyang
    opened on Mar 19, 2024 · edited by pytorch-bot
    Contributor
    Issue body actions

    🐛 Describe the bug

    Repro:

    import torch
import torch._dynamo

torch._dynamo.config.capture_scalar_outputs = True

torch.library.define("ezyang::split_with_sizes_and_clone", "(Tensor input, int[] sizes) -> Tensor[]")

def split_with_sizes_and_clone(input, sizes):
    return [t.clone() for t in torch.ops.aten.split_with_sizes.default(input, sizes)]

torch.library.impl("ezyang::split_with_sizes_and_clone", "default", split_with_sizes_and_clone)

@torch.library.impl_abstract("ezyang::split_with_sizes_and_clone")
def split_with_sizes_and_clone_abstract(input, sizes):
    # TODO: I'm lazy
    rs = torch.ops.aten.split_with_sizes.default(input, sizes)
    return [input.new_empty(r.size()) for r in rs]

@torch.compile()
def f(sz, x):
    s0, s1 = sz.tolist()
    r0, r1 = torch.ops.ezyang.split_with_sizes_and_clone.default(x, [s0, s1])
    return torch.ops.aten.sort.default(r1)

N = 7312
S0 = 420
S1 = N - S0

f(torch.tensor([S0, S1]), torch.randn(N))

    fails with

    torch._dynamo.exc.TorchRuntimeError: Failed running call_function ezyang.split_with_sizes_and_clone.default(*(FakeTensor(..., size=(7312,)), [u0, u1]), **{}):
ezyang::split_with_sizes_and_clone() Expected a value of type 'List[int]' for argument 'sizes' but instead found type 'immutable_list'.
Position: 1
Value: [u0, u1]
Declaration: ezyang::split_with_sizes_and_clone(Tensor input, int[] sizes) -> Tensor[]
Cast error details: Unable to cast Python instance of type <class 'torch.fx.immutable_collections.immutable_list'> to C++ type '?' (#define PYBIND11_DETAILED_ERROR_MESSAGES or compile in debug mode for details)

    Actually this has nothing to do with immutable_list though; I should have put SymInt in my schema rather than int. Would be good to have a better error in this case

    Hi @NiklasZ!

    Thank you so much for confirming that the issue is still reproducible on a recent build and for offering to submit a PR to improve the error handling. We really appreciate you jumping in to help!

    You've hit the nail on the head. You've correctly understood that the goal is to implement more meaningful error handling for this scenario. That's fantastic, and we're looking forward to your PR!

    To give you a bit more context, the core issue is that the error message is misleading. When a schema expects a list of integers (int[]) but receives a list containing symbolic integers (SymInts, which torch.compile uses), the error should clarify this type mismatch within the list's elements, rather than just pointing out the immutable_list container type.

    Your proposed approach sounds perfect: check for the condition where a function expects a list of integers but receives a list containing symbolic integers (SymInt), and when this specific type mismatch is detected, add a hint to the error message suggesting the use of SymInt[] instead of int[].

    Regarding implementation, while the error is triggered by the Python f(...) function call, the actual type casting and error generation happen in our C++ backend. The message Unable to cast Python instance... to C++ type is a great clue pointing in that direction. Have you had a chance to look into the C++ files that handle argument parsing for operators? That's likely the best place to add this check and the improved error message.

    This is an excellent issue to work on, and your plan sounds solid. For general guidance on contributing, you can always refer to our guide here: [CONTRIBUTING.md](https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md).

    Please don't hesitate to ask if you have any questions as you dig in. We're here to help. Looking forward to your contribution!
